  "text": "## Kubernetes Scheduler Binding to Kubelet Pod Admission Chain\n\nThe flow of a scheduler binding decision reaching the kubelet involves several key components:\n\n### 1. Scheduler Binding Decision\n**File**: `pkg/scheduler/scheduler.go`\nThe Scheduler struct manages the main scheduling loop. When a pod is ready to be scheduled, the scheduler runs the scheduling cycle.\n\n**File**: `pkg/scheduler/schedule_one.go` - `bind()` function (line 968)\nThis is where the binding decision is executed. After selecting a node, the scheduler calls `bind()` which invokes the framework's bind plugins.\n\n### 2. Default Binder Plugin\n**File**: `pkg/scheduler/framework/plugins/defaultbinder/default_binder.go`\nThe `DefaultBinder` struct implements the `BindPlugin` interface. Its `Bind()` method (line 51) creates a Binding object and calls:\n```go\nerr := b.handle.ClientSet().CoreV1().Pods(binding.Namespace).Bind(ctx, binding, metav1.CreateOptions{})\n```\nThis makes the actual API call to bind the pod.\n\n### 3. API Server Binding Handler\n**File**: `pkg/registry/core/pod/storage/storage.go`\nThe `BindingREST` struct (line 149) implements the REST endpoint for pod binding. Its `Create()` method (line 173) receives the binding request from the client and:\n\n1. Validates the binding object\n2. Calls `assignPod()` (line 259) which calls `setPodHostAndAnnotations()` (line 209)\n3. Updates the pod's `Spec.NodeName` field in etcd using `GuaranteedUpdate()`\n4. Sets the PodScheduled condition to True\n\nThe `setPodHostAndAnnotations()` function checks for scheduling gates (line 238) - if a pod has non-empty `spec.schedulingGates`, the binding is rejected.\n\n### 4. Kubelet Pod Watch from API Server\n**File**: `pkg/kubelet/config/apiserver.go`\nThe `NewSourceApiserver()` function (line 37) sets up a watch on the API server:\n- Creates a ListWatcher that watches pods with `spec.nodeName` equal to the kubelet's node name\n- Waits for the node to sync before starting the watch\n- Calls `newSourceApiserverFromLW()` (line 58) which:\n  - Creates a Reflector to watch pod changes\n  - Sends pod updates to the kubelet's configuration channel with update type `kubetypes.SET`\n\n### 5. Kubelet Pod Sync Loop\n**File**: `pkg/kubelet/kubelet.go`\nThe `syncLoop()` function (line 2387) is the main kubelet sync loop that:\n- Watches for pod updates from multiple sources (API server, file, HTTP)\n- Processes each pod update by calling the appropriate handler\n\n**File**: `pkg/kubelet/kubelet.go` - `HandlePodAdditions()` function (line 2640)\nWhen new pods are detected, this handler:\n1. Stores the pod in the pod manager\n2. Calls `canAdmitPod()` to check if the pod can be admitted\n3. If admission succeeds, calls `kl.podWorkers.UpdatePod()` with `UpdateType: kubetypes.SyncPodCreate`\n\n### 6. Pod Admission Gates\n**File**: `pkg/kubelet/kubelet.go` - `canAdmitPod()` function (line 2349)\nThis function checks if a pod can be admitted by:\n1. Collecting allocated pods on the node\n2. Iterating through registered `admitHandlers` (line 2355)\n3. Calling each handler's `Admit()` method with PodAdmitAttributes\n4. Rejecting the pod if any handler returns `Admit: false`\n\n**File**: `pkg/kubelet/lifecycle/interfaces.go`\nDefines the core admission interfaces:\n- `PodAdmitHandler` interface with `Admit()` method\n- `PodAdmitAttributes` struct containing the pod and other pods\n- `PodAdmitResult` with Admit, Reason, and Message fields\n\nAdmission handlers registered in kubelet.go include:\n- Eviction manager admission handler (line 947)\n- Sysctl allowlist handler (line 956)\n- Container manager resource allocation handler (line 966)\n- Predicate admission handler for node predicates (line 969)\n- AppArmor admission handler (line 978)\n- Shutdown manager handler (line 1014)\n\n**File**: `pkg/kubelet/lifecycle/handlers.go`\nThe `appArmorAdmitHandler` (line 213) implements AppArmor policy validation during pod admission.\n\n**File**: `pkg/kubelet/lifecycle/predicate.go`\nThe `NewPredicateAdmitHandler()` function creates an admission handler that checks node predicates and resource allocation constraints.\n\n### 7. Pod Worker Sync\n**File**: `pkg/kubelet/pod_workers.go`\nOnce admitted, the pod is processed by pod workers which call the `SyncPod()` method (the interface defined at line 254).\n\n**File**: `pkg/kubelet/kubelet.go` - `SyncPod()` method (line 1845)\nThis is where the actual pod synchronization happens:\n1. Generates API pod status\n2. Handles pod resource resizing\n3. Sets up networking\n4. Creates cgroups and applies resource limits\n5. Starts containers as specified in the pod definition\n\n## Summary\nThe complete chain flows as follows:\n1. Scheduler decides to bind pod → DefaultBinder.Bind()\n2. API call to BindingREST.Create() → updates pod.spec.nodeName in etcd\n3. Kubelet watches API server → receives pod update\n4. HandlePodAdditions() → checks canAdmitPod()\n5. Pod admission handlers evaluate constraints and gates\n6. If admitted → podWorkers.UpdatePod()\n7. SyncPod() → creates containers and runs the pod\n\nThe key admission gates include:\n- Scheduling gates (checked at API server binding time)\n- Node predicates (checked at kubelet admission time)\n- AppArmor policies\n- Resource allocation and eviction constraints\n- Sysctl allowlist validation"
}

